The Other Side of Global Warming: Ojai Valley Cooling

Olivia Whitener

2/6/2017

For the past few decades, the scientific community has been locked in a fierce debate over the issue of climate change. Those concerned about the future of the environment, known as alarmists, warn that increased carbon dioxide emissions and the resulting global temperature increase of about 1.7 degrees Fahrenheit since 1880 (NASA) will have disastrous effects on agriculture, ecosystems, water resources, and human health. With increased temperatures come the risks of heat waves, drought, early snow melt, and extreme weather events (EPA). Although skeptics may acknowledge increased temperatures, they deny that there is anything out of the ordinary that should cause humans to change behavior.

The Golden State of California, already known for its sunny skies and year-round palm trees, has been warming for the past century. Southern California specifically has experienced a dramatic temperature increase of about 3 degrees Fahrenheit in the past century. If this is the case, then why have the maximum temperatures (TMax) of more than half the year in Ojai, California decreased since 1920?

Ojai is a small town of about 7500 people situated in Ventura County, just northwest of Los Angeles and east of Santa Barbara. According to National Oceanic and Atmospheric Association climate data, the maximum temperatures in Ojai have decreased for seven out of twelve months of the year. Out of these seven months, five have p-values less than 0.05. This means the data is statistically significant and rejects the null hypothesis that there is no temperature change with time. Four of the five statistically significant months have decreasing temperatures.

Interestingly, while Ojai is experiencing a cooling trend in TMax for a majority of months of the year, there is an opposite phenomenon occurring with minimum temperatures (TMin). For 11 out of 12 months, Ojais minimum temperatures have increased. 8 out of these 11 months are statistically significant, with p-values less than 0.05. The one month with decreasing TMin, December, is not statistically significant.

What can explain these contrary trends? It is a phenomenon termed coastal cooling that occurs along the entire state of California. When inland temperatures increase due to increased concentration of greenhouse gases, coast to inland pressure and temperature gradients are affected. Curtis Ebbesmeyer found significant warming of the Pacific sea surface temperature over the last few decades, which would contribute to the cooling of coastal California. This causes increased sea breeze frequency, intensity, and/or duration. Therefore, the inland temperature increase from greenhouse gas emissions leads to a reverse reaction of cooling maximum temperatures in coastal regions.

Professor Robert Bornstein of San Jose State University, who is at the forefront of research for coastal cooling in California, has conducted research that reflects the temperature changes Ojai is experiencing. Observations done at both regional and global scales have already found that since the mid-1970s, the rate of asymmetric warming has accelerated. Asymmetric warming occurs when TMin increases at a faster rate than TMax, such as what is occurring in Ojai. Studies done by Moustafa Chahine and Aiguo Dai et al. show that asymmetric warming may be due to a vigorous hydrologic cycle (Nemani et al.), including higher amounts of evaporation, atmospheric water vapor, and precipitation. Bornsteins data collection for the South Coast Air Basin area and San Francisco Bay Area show that both TMin and TMax have increased for inland sites, while coastal sites in those regions have simultaneously had rising TMins and falling TMaxes. This discrepancy leads to what appears to be an unchanging average temperature. However, relying solely on the average temperature trendline obscures the descreasing maximum temperatures caused by coastal cooling. This neglects the disruption of the seasonal cycle and potentially harmful impacts. Bornsteins study concluded that 1970-2005, the overall trend in degrees Celsius per decade for the South Coast Air Basin was: TMin +0.16 for inland areas, +0.28 for coastal areas TMax +0.32 for inland areas, -0.30 for coastal areas

This 1950-2000 model of annual summer temperatures (in Celsius) shows decreasing warming rates towards the coast. The boxes are San Francisco Bay Area (SFBA) and South Coast Air Basin (SoCAB) regions. National Weather Service Cooperative Observer sites.

1970-2005 South Coast Air Basin summer TMax warming and cooling trends (in Celsius). Solid circles show p-values < 0.01, crossed circles show p-values of 0.05, and open circles are not significant.

The temperature trends for inland sites in SoCAB and SFBA show that both TMin and TMax increased.

Coastal sites in SoCAB and SFBA, however, had rising TMins and falling TMaxes, leading to what appears to be an unchanging average temperature.

So what does this all mean? Amidst the warnings of global warmings destructive impacts on both humans and the environment, any news of cooling should sound like a blessing. The phenomenon of coastal cooling does mean less energy needed for home and building cooling and lower rates of human heat stress.

However, for a town like Ojai rich in organic agriculture, this cooling trend could take a big toll. Although the scientific discussion has predominantly been focused around negative effects of increased temperatures on crops, these effects reflect the significant (and potentially dangerous) influences temperature change can have on the worlds food supply. Plants are biologically adapted to certain climate conditions, so higher temperatures may exceed the optimum for reproductive development. The USDA Climate Change Science Program 2008 report found that warming temperatures in the western United States have led to increased summer drought stress, vulnerability to insect pests, and fire hazard. Increased minimum temperatures and warmer springs extend the range and lifetime of many pests that can damage crops. Hotter climate also leads to increased evaporation and altered precipation cycles, which contribute to drought, such as the one California has experienced for the past 6 years. Even apparent benefits such as longer growing seasons would simultaneously suffer from effects such as decreased water availability.

Climate is a significant influence in almost every step of corp production, from temperature variability and humidity levels to frost intensity and duration (Nemani et al.). Although more research needs to be done on the effects of cooling temperatures on agricultural production, the unnatural altering of the seasons will undoubtedly influence the growth of Ojais crops. The ability of plants to adapt to such changes is gradual and can be hindered when changes are so swift. Some of the effects can be inferred from what has been studied about rising temperatures, such as cooler temperatures causing shorter growing seasons, therefore reducing yield. Oranges are particularly susceptible to cold. According to horticulturist Dr.William Johnson, citrus fruits easily freeze at 79 to 82 degrees Fahrenheit. Ojais variety of citrus fruits are grown through different periods of the year, but temperatures dipping to high 60s, low 70s in November and December could damage many breeds, such as Navel and Valencia oranges, Satsuma mandarins, and Eureka lemons.

Olive oil is also one of Ojais most popular products, with the Ojai Olive Oil Company being ranked the #1 attraction in Ojai on Trip Advisor (Ojai Olive Oil). Leandro Ravetti, technical director of Australias largest olive oil producer conducted a study that found frost is one of the most important hazards to the olive industry and caused significant economic losses for Australia. Damage to olive fruits in turn colors olive oil with an unpleasant taste. Though temperatures in California may not fall low enough to produce frost, the trend of decreasing maximum temperatures could cause chilling injuries that would similarly affect the quality of olive oil.

However, the increase in Ojais minimum temperatures also decreases frost frequency and increases frost-free growing season length (Nemani et al.). As mentioned earlier, this could put a strain on Californias soil quality and water demand. Ultimately, more research must be done to evaluate the effects of decreasing maximum temperatures and increasing minimum temperatures in Ojai. Not only is there asymmetric warming, where TMin is warming at a faster rate than TMax, but there is also general cooling of TMax in the later half of the year. These changes in climate could have significant effects on the agriculture of Ojai, particularly the primary crops of citruses and olives.
